  "prompt": "What is the status of net neutrality in all countries?",
  "response": "As of my last knowledge update in October 2023, the status of net neutrality varies significantly from country to country. Here\u2019s a general overview:\n\n1. **United States**: The Federal Communications Commission (FCC) repealed net neutrality regulations in 2017. Since then, there have been ongoing discussions and efforts at both state and federal levels to either restore regulations or create new frameworks for internet service providers (ISPs). Some states have implemented their own net neutrality laws.\n\n2. **European Union**: The EU has strong net neutrality rules in place, established in 2016 under the Open Internet Regulation. These rules prohibit ISPs from blocking or throttling legal content or services, ensuring that all internet traffic is treated equally.\n\n3. **Canada**: The Canadian Radio-television and Telecommunications Commission (CRTC) has upheld net neutrality principles, stating that ISPs cannot discriminate against specific types of traffic.\n\n4. **India**: The Telecom Regulatory Authority of India (TRAI) mandated net neutrality in 2018, prohibiting ISPs from blocking, throttling, or prioritizing any content or services.\n\n5. **Australia**: Australia does not have explicit net neutrality laws, but there is a general consensus and a regulatory framework that supports open internet principles, although this is less formalized compared to the EU or India.\n\n6. **Latin America**: Different countries have varying stances. Some, like Brazil, have enacted strong net neutrality laws (Marco Civil da Internet), while others do not have explicit regulations.\n\n7. **China**: China operates under a system of strict internet regulation and censorship, effectively negating the principles of net neutrality in favor of state control over internet content.\n\n8. **Countries in Africa**: The status of net neutrality in African countries varies widely, with some nations adopting regulations that support openness and others lacking clear guidelines. Internet access and policies are still evolving in many regions.\n\n9. **Other Regions**: Various other regions\u2014like Southeast Asia\u2014exhibit diverse approaches to net neutrality, with some countries enforcing strict regulations, while others have no specific laws or commonly accepted practices regarding net neutrality.\n\nThe status of net neutrality is subject to change, so it is advisable to refer to the latest information or specific regulatory bodies in each country for the most current developments.",
